No one at the time was claimimg such, despite the quote. What was experimental was taking the musical practice and applying it in a pop music context. The means simply weren't available for that to easily come together before the 60s onwards.

A lot of the cultural emphasis on rhythm and melody just comes from the means available. In West Africa percussive instruments were more predominant, while in Western Europe strings were. The former is primarily made to express rhythm, the latter harmony.
So it's not surprising that a bunch of people using an instrument you've never used with a composition that emphasis different aspects of music would come up with something you haven't.

a common rhythm, especially with hip-hop and modern drum patterns, is having your kick on the one and a snare, clap or other mid range perc on the 2 and 4. And Magma was initially against/iffy against calling their music "celestial". While "zeuhl" by itself translates to Celestial, the phrase "Zeuhl wortz" more specifically meant to "Music of universal might" which was what Magma is trying to invoke.

Even in the 1980s, French zeuhl groups like Dun and Shub-Niggurath all heavily deviated from Magma's style of zeuhl, because that's quite literally what genres do. Bands evolve and deviate into new sounds within that genre.

Ruins sounds the way they do because Tatsuya Yoshida liked groups like Magma (Vander is his fucking idol) and regular prog groups like Gentle Giant and wanted to play Magma-inspired music but he also wanted to introduce the energy of hardcore punk and extreme metal into zeuhl. In essence Ruins is just the more chaotic parts of Magma stripped down to only a drummer and a bassist since they couldn't find a guitarist in Japan who could keep up with the style of music they wanted to make.
Nothing sounded like Ruins in the late 80s but their music was still progressive and they had nothing in common with punk or metal beyond extremity, had a very clear Magma influence that it got labeled zeuhl because that's what it resembled more than anything else and pioneered a new time of extreme, technical zeuhl, but also simultaneously pioneered mathcore and brutal prog as well.

>>114362822
>"'Brutal Prog' was a term coined by The Flying Luttenbachers leader Weasel Walter on the 'avant-progressive' listserve in 2000 to delineate an aesthetic within the general idiom of Progressive Rock which is more focused on dissonance and intensity than traditional 'prog'. Brutal Prog is not an organized movement in any way, but rather a term to delineate newer, more extreme bands from the traditional trappings of what is known as Progressive Rock.

>The so-called brutal prog bands seem to have strong roots in or a likeness to one or more of the following historical aesthetics: DIY/punk attitude and aggression; the econconstructivist/nihilistic 'No Wave' ethos; characteristics of the Rock in Opposition (RIO) movement from Europe; musical influence from some of the darker traditional Progressive Rock bands; or the music of Japanese cult bands.

>Despite adventurous attitudes towards structure and meter, many classic 'prog' bands like Yes or Genesis focused on harmonic consonance, with diatonic tonality prevaling. Brutal Prog bands are generally more challenging harmonically, often engaging sophisticated approaches to dissonance. For many of the groups there is also an emphasis on speed or sonic extremity for its own sake. Audio fidelity is sometimes sacrificed in the name of rawness or urgency."

>>114347185
Stage manager guy here. Two things to consider...
There's not much work to do in temrs of PR or business relations. I'm assuming you're American, I don't know how the IRS deals with the status of musician/artist, but it's generally considered a liberal profession so the paperwork isn't the biggest deal. You could do it all by yourself, given you've followed a short training course. There are ways to learn how to position yourself as a musician properly, doing the paperwork, networking, joining a scene, a label, etc. Leave your personality at the door because it's the least important thing when what you want to do is work.
The music industry is not the most competitive environment. There are places that look for muscians to book shows. If you're good enough, you can go basically everywhere, booking artists is a low-risk high-reward endeavor (which makes it difficult for artists to earn a living as well). That's if you do live shows. If you just make music in your home to release on the Internet, that's another story.
Finally, if your goal is to be famous or rich, tough shit because some people still don't know who Jimi Hendrix is. You can't possibly make a living out of music, some of the biggest names out there are broke as shit. You like your job as a musician or you quit and do carpentry or whatever. That's how it goes. That's why I'm a stage manager now, and I was lucky, and it's far from the safest job, but it brings food on the table.

Honestly you could throw a dart at any of the theory books and not really go wrong, ONLY as long as you read multiple texts. I've seen music professors RAIL against the Kostka, like it was the worst thing ever concocted by man. How much of the complaining is bullshit, who knows. You may as well read it, but again I would supplement with other books too.
Harmony and Voice Leading probably isn't the most appropriate book on second thought. It will give you a good foundation, but it is not very forgiving. I've heard good things about Burstein/Straus's Concise Introduction to Tonal Harmony, so you may give that a shot.

This is all I got. Aeternam's first album was great but they kinda fell off after that. The Animals as Leaders was ok but the production felt sterile and kinda ruined it. The new Abstract Illusion was bad compared to their first album.

Nite came out of nowhere and dropped the best heavy metal with Darth Vader vocals of the century. Very enjoyable guitars. Astral Spectre was also kinda cool and sounded like a 70s band trying to imitate Sigh. Was decent. Was also nice to see the Akercocke lads were back at it with a new project that had surprisingly good guitars and songwriting. Definitely one of the more enjoyable black- albums of the year.
Owls Woods Graves was my AOTY band for like 6 months just because of the group vocals. The Cult of Luna wasn't bad at all and actually had some varied, good songwriting. Truchło Strzygi swooped in with the underrated black metal release OTY. Morbid Stench brought the riffs and Depressive Witches was some interesting last-minute Inquisition worship with "epic black metal" tendencies. Also Elder are still writing good rock/honorary metal music

Aye buy a microphone, some extra instruments for layering and get a daw anon. Also your Soundcloud link is giving me user-numbers, worth changing that in the edit section. I listened to the first two tracks and it reminds a lot of my first recordings; done on a phone, minimalist and very lo-fi. I feel like you know what you want to improve, I hear potential. The melody and chord progression on track two was sweet and pretty. Track one was fun. Solid for a first effort, keep moving upwards anon.
>>114341228
Being a shoegazey track, I'll start by saying that the guitars sound really nice. I like the swelling fuzz you've got going on. The drums were a bit thin in the mix and I can tell there were vocals but they were mixed at the level of a background effect. Good haziness all around, coulda been denser or had tighter songwriting but it works well loud.
>>114341325
Joy Division. I had to say it. It's clearly a big influence. That said, that is a pretty well made track. Nice guitar harmonies and the lower vocals fit well. Drum machine sounds solid, the reverb on it makes it sound a bit more in-the-room. The biggest thing holding it back for me is the Joy Division influence, it sounds heavily borrowed.
>>114341506
Why are you shilling here? I had to click the 'more' button on the supporters like three times kek. Well done anon. I'm about a minute into the opener and it makes sense, this is catchy and tight. There's a lot of chord movement and that bending effect(?) makes it even harder to discern, it's harmonically doing flips. I dig that. Compliments to the bassist, interesting lines. This is a very nice balance of punk energy with shoegaze/psych effects. Good layering. That psychedelic tail on the end was not my favourite part but it didn't overstay itself and probably makes for a good transition. Cool track.

do you play brass? trombone players always seem to love shostakovich in my experience. if you do - listen to his string quartets (nos 8 and 9 are my fav, but no 15 is best if you like a more minimalist approach). if you play a bowed string instrument, i probably don't have to say more
>listen to fire! orchestra
yeah, i have. i think i like scandinavian contemporary jazz more the fewer instruments there are on stage (to an extent), so the music is very hit or miss. as much as i love mats gustafsson (who is an adorably sweet person, btw), fire! orchestra misses me. (same with albums like the death defying unicorn and gard nilssens supersonic orchestra, but maybe you'd like those). imo this style of contemporary jazz is done far better on albums like koma saxo live or hegge's the creator has a bachelor plan.

I assumed you were making a reference to the theater Rael emerged from, but the lyrics didn't say anything of film, but after reading the plot
https://docs.google.com/document/edit?id=1ITGpu-3WK7bTSTLxefdQGC0O6renCkka7LH4cKkxHwU#
By "film stock," are referring to the "wall of death" windshield, pic related?
If so, I don't think he forgot about it. He never left it.

What happens is that Rael is caught against the wall along with the other characters of Broadway, making the visual collage on the "film" that is the "Broadway Melody Of 1974." As this song fades out and we enter Cuckoo Cocoon, the wall has consumed all, leaving Rael in its void. I never thought of it until now, but in a way the world with the wall is "developing" like a piece of film at this point, as Rael points out more and more defined features as Cuckoo Cocoon becomes In the Cage. Personally, I see In The Cage as the first area for people who fell into this world, acting as both a pressure chamber from the outside world and a conversion chamber one needs to go through to survive the otherworld (like the "keep on turning" being a sort of centrifuge). And once processed in the cage, Rael once again loses control of his body and is just transported by the forces in the cage area to the "factory," which I assume anyone besides Rael would also go through.
Basically the film stock/windshield, while being some sort of substance, ultimately acts like a portal or a limina- I mean tranisitional zone that brings Rael completely under and into the underground recreation of NYC.

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Celluloid

My interpretation is that Brother John is not his actual sibling (shocker), but is actually a part of Rael's self that got seperated from his whole during the events of "Fly on a Windshield" and reformed as the personality "Brother John" like Rael was reformed during "Cuckoo Cucoon." This is why we see no mention of him until "In the Cage" - John simply did not exist independently until then - and why they ultimately join back together as one. Furthermore, I think Brother John is the aspect of Rael's being that triggered the whole story, by being the part of him that was guiding him to an unforntunate end that begged intervention through the "Wall of Death," either as some unconcious cosmic correction or the act of some entity. I base this mainly on:

A. Rael and John are the only characters to complete or even make progress through this world, despite the presence of many living beings along the way, many seemingly human and appearing either trapped, crippled, simply unable to proceed.
B. When John first appears, he is *outside* of the cages - unlike Rael and the other countless prisoners - and free to proceed without Rael which he does, while Rael has to wait. I interpret this as the universe itself being aware of what is occurring with these two characters, and this either being a test of John's commitment to Rael (which he fails), or just being ignored over Rael as ultimately John cannot save himself.
C. Everytime he is encountered he displays his dark personality traits and makes decisions that affirm his first failure.

So the whole Lamb story is Rael going through a metaphorical and literal life-and-death struggle to get him and his "brother" out of this underworld, and in the process reuniting with himself and achieving self-realization.

>>114353139
They weren't chasing it. They were making bags of money off touring and merch (which was easy to cook the books on, because in the 70's that was a straight cash business), the albums weren't that important to them. They managed to bypass the industry bullshit and started their own label, and kept all the money off smaller sales numbers, like Zappa did.
The downside was that they didn't have a label marketing them, or doing payola to get them played. They were played on college radio and late night on independant AOR stations, though - and, their stuff was too long for most station's format.
It's not a coincidence that when they later signed to Arista, they got marketing and had songs like "Touch Of Grey" pushed, and got it to chart. Or that they had a lot of push when they were on Warners for their first 5 albums - the 70's only had their own label releasing stuff, and they didn't push it themselves.
But, they were lazy, and capitulated and went to Arista, and they made more inroads commercially because of it. They would have been a lot bigger if they'd signed with another label in the 70's, commercially.

posts.com:
>Elvis Costello Live 1977 Chicago
>First generation pop-punk, British Power Pop
This has been released under the titles Armed and Dangerous, as well as Exit, but this is the actual soundboard recording used for the WXRT "Unconcert" broadcast in 1978. (Called Unconcert because it was sponsored by 7-Up, The "Un-Cola") Believe it or not, Tom Petty and The Heartbreakers were the opening act at this show. This was just before Elvis Costello and The Attractions made their debut on Saturday Night Live, subbing for The Sex Pistols who cancelled. (THANKS, MALCOLM!) My Aim is True had just been released, but This Year's Model was just a few months away. (Songs from TYM were played at this show)
When you listen to this concert, you'll understand immediately why Elvis Costello and The Attractions were considered a "Punk" band, and why the first generation of punk rockers adopted them as their own until 1980.

Again, no video. My apologies.

>In this final couplet, Kendrick Lamar employs a rhetorical move akin to–and in its way even more devastating than–Common’s move in the last line of “I Used to Love H.E.R.”: snapping an entire lyric into place with a surprise revelation of something hitherto left unspoken. In “H.E.R.”, Common reveals the identity of the song’s “her”–hip hop itself–forcing the listener to re-evaluate the entire meaning and intent of the song. Common’s “her” is not a woman but hip hop itself; Lamar’s “I” is not (or not only) Kendrick Lamar but his community as a whole. The only Bowie Album I can listen from beginning to end is one critics hate, Diamond Dogs.
And I guess, it also applies to both Low and Heroes, but I consider the instrumental pieces of those albums, close to ambient, as much easier to compose than a good engaging, interesting song.

The other albums have filler or some plain bad songs. Hunky Dory is one of the best Bowie albums, with at least half a dozen great songs (Life on Mars, Queen Bitch, Andy Warhol, Quicksand, Oh You Pretty Things, The Bewley Brothers) but the rest is pretty much trash, like A Song for Bob Dylan.

Ziggy is close to very good from beginning to End, and could have been a 10/10 if he had replaced the couple of weak tracks with some songs he wasted in non albums, like John I'm Only Dancing or All the Young Dudes, he was at his creative peak in that period

The 80s music of Bowie is mostly trash, except for a few singles. His first good album in more than a decade, the first one since Scary Monsters, was the soundtrack Buddah of Suburbia which you didn't listen to, it's from 1993 iirc

I divide the career of Bowie in 4
Before Hunky Dory, from Hunky Dory to Scary Monsters, from Let's Dance to Black Tie White Noise, and from Buddha of Suburbia on until his death
I see periods 1 and 3 as mostly bad, and periods 2 and 4 as mostly good.
